<mxfile host="app.diagrams.net" type="device"><diagram name="Train to crazy town" id="train-to-crazy-town"><mxGraphModel dx="1400" dy="900" grid="1" gridSize="10" guides="1" tooltips="1" connect="1" arrows="1" fold="1" page="1" pageScale="1" pageWidth="1600" pageHeight="2400" math="0" shadow="0"><root><mxCell id="0"/><mxCell id="1" parent="0"/><mxCell id="band_0" value="STOP 0" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#6b7f96;fontColor=#6b7f96;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="549" y="-30" width="230" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="band_1" value="STOP 1" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#5a9367;fontColor=#5a9367;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="527" y="193" width="273" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="band_2" value="STOP 2" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#b0a04a;fontColor=#b0a04a;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="524" y="416" width="280" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="band_3" value="STOP 3" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#c9932a;fontColor=#c9932a;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="488" y="639" width="352" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="band_4" value="STOP 4" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#c96a4a;fontColor=#c96a4a;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="339" y="862" width="632" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="band_5" value="STOP 5" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#c0392b;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="48" y="1085" width="839" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="band_6" value="STOP 6" style="rounded=1;html=1;dashed=1;dashPattern=6 4;strokeWidth=2;fillColor=none;verticalAlign=top;align=left;spacingLeft=12;spacingTop=6;fontStyle=1;fontSize=13;strokeColor=#6a3fa0;fontColor=#6a3fa0;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="-22" y="1308" width="761" height="144" as="geometry"/></mxCell><mxCell id="e0" value="drop nationality discount" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#8a5fb0;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s0_parochial" target="s1_all_humans"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="664" y="127"/><mxPoint x="664" y="175"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e1" value="add animal welfare range" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#8a5fb0;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s1_all_humans" target="s2_animals"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="664" y="350"/><mxPoint x="664" y="398"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e2" value="add invertebrate sentience" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#8a5fb0;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s2_animals" target="s3_inverts"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="664" y="573"/><mxPoint x="664" y="621"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e3" value="count soil / wild animals" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#c0392b;dashed=1;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s3_inverts" target="s4_soil"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="702" y="796"/><mxPoint x="726" y="845"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e4" value="stop discounting the future" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#c0392b;dashed=1;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s3_inverts" target="s4_future"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="588" y="797"/><mxPoint x="541" y="847"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e5" value="add pure-time discount" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#c0392b;dashed=1;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s4_future" target="s5_discount"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="468" y="1019"/><mxPoint x="474" y="1067"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e6" value="add P(nuclear war)/yr" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#c0392b;dashed=1;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s4_future" target="s5_nuclear"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="565" y="1020"/><mxPoint x="633" y="1071"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e7" value="accept astronomical waste" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#8a5fb0;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s4_future" target="s5_astro"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="364" y="1020"/><mxPoint x="306" y="1071"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e8" value="only my pleasure is real" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#c0392b;dashed=1;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s5_astro" target="s6_boltzmann"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="177" y="1242"/><mxPoint x="162" y="1291"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><mxCell id="e9" value="deny moral realism" style="edgeStyle=none;curved=1;html=1;endArrow=block;endFill=1;strokeColor=#9aa6b3;fontSize=9;fontColor=#5b6675;strokeColor=#c0392b;dashed=1;" edge="1" parent="1" source="s5_astro" target="s6_antirealist"><mxGeometry relative="1" as="geometry"><Array as="points"><mxPoint x="316" y="1244"/><mxPoint x="386" y="1294"/></Array></mxGeometry></mxCell><object label="Parochial&lt;br&gt;community + nation&lt;br&gt;→ Local soup kitchen&lt;br&gt;(common-sense default)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Only my family + community count&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Least-crazy end of the line. What matters is humans in my family and local community, in the present generation. Moral weight only on people near me; heavy pure-time discount; humans only; only near-certain, measurable effects count. Distant strangers, animals and the future are outside the circle (weight 0), so the local option wins. The agreed basis for the soup kitchen is a worked BOTEC: people made happier per dollar times their wellbeing gain, netted against the counterfactual of the money sitting in a bank (which still does ~30% as much good). Every node downstream imports THIS number unchanged. The pre-EA commonsense baseline; no single EA figure defends it." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s0_parochial.squiggle" id="s0_parochial"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#dfe7ef;strokeColor=#6b7f96;fontColor=#1b2733;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="571" y="0" width="186" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Humanitarian&lt;br&gt;all present humans&lt;br&gt;→ GiveWell top charity (AMF)&lt;br&gt;(Alexander Berger)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;All present humans count equally&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Flip: drop the nationality discount (Peter Singer&#x27;s famine argument is the origin). What matters is people in the present generation, wherever they live. A life saved abroad counts like a life saved at home, so cheap, measurable global-health and cash interventions dominate. Alexander Berger is the prominent exemplar of deliberately getting off the train here and staying with robust, evidence-backed global health &amp; wellbeing (GiveWell / Open Phil). The soup kitchen&#x27;s agreed DALY is still carried through untouched; it is simply no longer the best buy." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s1_all_humans.squiggle" id="s1_all_humans"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#cfe6cf;strokeColor=#5a9367;fontColor=#1e3a24;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="549" y="223" width="229" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Farmed&lt;br&gt;animals count&lt;br&gt;→ The Humane League&lt;br&gt;(Peter Singer, Lewis Bollard)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Nonhuman animals count (welfare range)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Flip: extend the moral circle to farmed vertebrates, weighted by a sentience-adjusted welfare range (neuron-count exponent). Peter Singer (Animal Liberation) is the canonical articulator; Lewis Bollard leads Open Phil&#x27;s farm-animal-welfare work. Corporate welfare campaigns avert enormous suffering per dollar and overtake human global health under most welfare-range estimates." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s2_animals.squiggle" id="s2_animals"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#e6e2c0;strokeColor=#b0a04a;fontColor=#3a3410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="546" y="446" width="236" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Invertebrates&lt;br&gt;count&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project  (UNSTABLE)  ▼&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Invertebrates count (neuron-count exponent)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Flip: count invertebrates, with welfare range ~ (neuron count)^exponent. Brian Tomasik is the prominent voice on insect / invertebrate suffering. This is the worked example of the train&#x27;s instability: sweeping the exponent from 0 to 2 swings shrimp welfare range across ~12 orders of magnitude and flips the ranking (edit neuron_exponent in this stop&#x27;s `sets` to watch the top pick move). It is the FORK point: the tree splits here into a soil-animal branch (A) and a longtermist branch (F)." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s3_inverts.squiggle" id="s3_inverts"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#f6e0c0;strokeColor=#c9932a;fontColor=#5a3f10;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="510" y="669" width="308" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Soil animals&lt;br&gt;count (branch A)&lt;br&gt;→ GiveWell top charity (AMF)  (sign uncertain)&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Soil / wild invertebrates count (sign uncertain)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Branch A (biological micro-minds): once you count the ~10^19 soil animals affected by land use, GiveWell top charities&#x27; cropland effect works out to ~1.11 kQALY/$ (~1.74x the Shrimp Welfare Project Humane Slaughter Initiative). The &#x27;normal&#x27; human charity leaps to ~1.11e5x GiveWell&#x27;s own direct value - and its SIGN is uncertain (it could be net-negative for soil nematodes). This branch has no Squiggle model yet: there is no comparable published soil-animal BOTEC to copy, so it is not fabricated." id="s4_soil"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#f2ccc0;strokeColor=#c96a4a;fontColor=#5a2410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="590" y="892" width="359" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Future&lt;br&gt;people count&lt;br&gt;→ ALLFED  ▼&lt;br&gt;(Ajeya Cotra, Toby Ord)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Future people count (low/zero time discount)&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Branch F (longtermist): stop discounting future lives (future_discount stays 1). Toby Ord (The Precipice) and Will MacAskill (What We Owe The Future) are the prominent longtermists; Ajeya Cotra coined the &#x27;train to crazy town&#x27; metaphor and rides roughly to here via worldview diversification. Reducing global-catastrophic risk (e.g. ALLFED&#x27;s civilisational-resilience work) starts to dominate present-focused giving. This node is itself a FORK: below it sit near-identical children that differ by exactly one added term - a pure-time discount, a raised P(nuclear war), or the fanatical x-risk tail. The fanatical tail is still refused here (accept_tiny_prob: false)." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s4_future.squiggle" id="s4_future"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#f2ccc0;strokeColor=#c96a4a;fontColor=#5a2410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="361" y="892" width="193" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Future&lt;br&gt;discounted&lt;br&gt;→ GiveWell top charity (AMF)&lt;br&gt;(Frank Ramsey)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Future people count, but pure-time-discounted&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Sibling of the longtermist stop, one term different: keep future people in the circle but apply a positive pure-time discount rate (future_discount 0.2). This is the cleanest illustration of the tree&#x27;s mimicry - the whole calculation is identical to its parent except for a single multiplicative discount term on the future_human domain. A modest discount is enough to pull the winner back toward present, measurable global health." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s5_discount.squiggle" id="s5_discount"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#eeb3b3;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#5a1410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="371" y="1115" width="229" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Nuclear war&lt;br&gt;non-negligible&lt;br&gt;→ ALLFED&lt;br&gt;(Carl Sagan, Martin Hellman)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Non-negligible P(nuclear war) per year&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Another one-term sibling: accept a non-negligible annual probability of nuclear war. The only change from the parent is a catastrophe multiplier (catastrophe_mult 50) that raises the value of future-protecting and resilience work; every other line of the calculation is copied. Civilisational-resilience work (ALLFED) dominates because it directly buys down the tail it now takes seriously." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s5_nuclear.squiggle" id="s5_nuclear"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#eeb3b3;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#5a1410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="636" y="1115" width="229" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Astronomical&lt;br&gt;stakes&lt;br&gt;→ AI safety (Redwood Research)&lt;br&gt;(Nick Bostrom, Eliezer Yudkowsky)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Astronomical waste + tiny-probability bets count&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Accept Nick Bostrom&#x27;s astronomical-waste argument and take small-probability / huge-payoff bets at face value (accept_tiny_prob flips true, releasing the fanatical tail); Eliezer Yudkowsky pushes AI-risk reasoning to its stark conclusions. Existential-risk reduction dominates everything. This is the far end Cotra&#x27;s near-termist deliberately gets off before; ride further and the last two stops stop being about charity at all." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s5_astro.squiggle" id="s5_astro"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#eeb3b3;strokeColor=#c0392b;fontColor=#5a1410;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="70" y="1115" width="265" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Boltzmann brain&lt;br&gt;hedonic solipsism&lt;br&gt;→ Local soup kitchen  (all equal)&lt;br&gt;(Ludwig Boltzmann)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;Only my own present pleasure is real&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Off the end of the line: if you are more likely a fleeting Boltzmann brain than an embodied agent, the only thing that matters is whatever makes you personally happy right now. This override INVALIDATES every assumption above it: the moral circle, welfare ranges, discounting and x-risk all stop mattering, and every charity collapses to the same low, pleasant-thought level of DALY (boltzmann_level). Nothing you do for anyone else registers, so the ranking goes flat - there is no best buy." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s6_boltzmann.squiggle" id="s6_boltzmann"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#d7c6e6;strokeColor=#6a3fa0;fontColor=#2c1650;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="0" y="1338" width="265" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Moral anti-realism&lt;br&gt;nothing matters&lt;br&gt;→ Local soup kitchen  (all negative - keep your money)&lt;br&gt;(J. L. Mackie)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;There is no moral fact; better to be selfish&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The other terminus: if moral realism is false there is no stance-independent reason to help anyone, so from the only perspective left - your own - every dollar given away is a dollar of personal value lost. This override sets ALL DALYs negative: the whole ranking inverts and the &#x27;best&#x27; charity is merely the least self-costly. The consistent recommendation is to keep the money; the soup kitchen shows up on top only because it moves the least." link="https://github.com/morganrivers/train_to_crazy_town/blob/main/squiggle/nodes/s6_antirealist.squiggle" id="s6_antirealist"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#d7c6e6;strokeColor=#6a3fa0;fontColor=#2c1650;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="302" y="1338" width="416" height="92" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object></root></mxGraphModel></diagram></mxfile>